        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "shalt have no portion on this side the river",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is not quite clear whether the river intended here and in ver. 10 is the Euphrates or the Jordan. Generally in the Old Testament ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "hannahar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " means the Euphrates, but the exaggeration is gross if that river was intended here. Only twice in their history had the Israelites advanced their frontier as far as that stream - under Solomon (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 4:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") and under Menahem (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 15:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); in their present depressed condition it was absurd to imagine that they could rival those early glories. But jealousy does not stop to weigh the reasonableness of its accusations. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
